    <text id="R13770402T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Union General Franz Sigel writes the Adjutant General concerning May, 1864,
                    Confederate movements in Virginia. He reports on a Confederate cavalry retreat
                    toward Staunton.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>
        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    <name type="recipient">ADJUTANT-GEN. U. S. ARMY,<lb/> Washington:</name>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1864-05-07">May 7, 1864--3.30 p.m.<lb/> (Received 12 midnight.)</date>
                        <name type="place">NEAR WINCHESTER, VA.,</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute/>
                </opener>
                <p>There is no strong force of the enemy between here and Woodstock. Our cavalry
                    occupied Strasburg and Front Royal on a reconnaissance, and part of it was as
                    far as Woodstock. The enemy's cavalry, about 200, retired from Woodstock toward
                    Staunton. Two battalions of rebel cavalry are at Luray. Mosby's cavalry is in
                    Loudoun Country. Please inform me how many regiments in all have been ordered to
                    this department.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute/>
                    <signed>F. SIGEL,<lb/> Maj.-Gen.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
